'''Walter Mellor''' (1880-1940) was an [[United States|American]] architect.

==Biography==
===Early life===
He was born on April 25, 1880 in [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name="philadelphia">[http://www.philadelphiabuildings.org/pab/app/ar_display.cfm/26898 Philadelphia Architects and Buildings]</ref><ref name="pacific">[https://digital.lib.washington.edu/architect/architects/2763/ Pacific Coast Architecture Database]</ref> His father was Alfred Mellor and his mother, Isabella (Latham) Mellor. He graduated from [[The Haverford School]] in [[Haverford, Pennsylvania]] in 1897 and received a Bachelor of Science in Mechanical Engineering from [[Haverford College]] in 1901.<ref name="philadelphia"/><ref name="pacific"/><ref name="countrylife">'Six Architects Who Are Designing Notable Country Residences', ''[[Country Life (magazine)|Country Life]]'', Volume 40, page 47 [http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lP0hAQAAMAAJ&pg=RA5-PA47&lpg=RA5-PA47&dq=walter+mellor+architect&source=bl&ots=hjl9lJTDRN&sig=t4UVq6LxuwGCOhAkOncnXnJ18kY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=jrL4UfmiAuvRiAKel4HoCA&ved=0CEoQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=walter%20mellor%20architect&f=false]</ref> He then earned a Bachelor of Science in Architecture from the [[University of Pennsylvania]] in 1904.<ref name="philadelphia"/><ref name="pacific"/><ref name="countrylife"/> He was a member of the [[Phi Gamma Delta]] fraternity.

===Career===
Shortly after graduation, he worked for [[Theophilus P. Chandler, Jr.]] (1845-1928), where he met [[Arthur Ingersoll Meigs]] (1882-1956).<ref name="philadelphia"/><ref name="countrylife"/> In 1906, they started their own architectural firm, with offices in the [[Lafayette Building (Philadelphia)| Lafayette Building]].<ref name="philadelphia"/><ref name="countrylife"/> They worked on alterations of the [[Pickering Hunt Club]] in [[Phoenixville, Pennsylvania]] in 1911 and the [[Princeton Charter Club]] in [[Princeton, New Jersey]] in 1913.<ref name="philadelphia"/> They also designed fraternity houses for Phi Gamma Delta and Haverford College.<ref name="philadelphia"/>

In 1916, [[George Howe (architect)|George Howe]] (1886<U+2013>1955) joined their practice.<ref name="philadelphia"/><ref name="countrylife"/> Together, they designed a branch office building for the [[Philadelphia Savings Fund Society]].<ref name="philadelphia"/> They also designed [[Phi Gamma Delta]] [[fraternity]] house at the [[University of Washington]] located at 5404 17th Avenue NE University District in [[Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]].<ref name="pacific"/><ref>[https://digital.lib.washington.edu/architect/structures/5605/ Pacific Coast Architectural Database: University of Washington, Seattle, Phi Gamma Delta House]</ref> In 1922, the firm won an award from the Philadelphia chapter of the [[American Institute of Architects]] for the McCracken residence in [[Germantown, Philadelphia]], and in 1925, the Gold Medal of the [[Architectural League of New York]] for the Newbold Estate development.<ref name="philadelphia"/> In 1928, Howe left the practice.<ref name="philadelphia"/>

He was a fellow of the American Institute of Architects and a member of the [[Philadelphia Art Alliance]], the [[Union League of Philadelphia]], the [[Philadelphia Zoological Society]], the [[Germantown Cricket Club]], the [[T-Square Club]] and the [[Mask and Wig]] Club.<ref name="philadelphia"/> He served on the Board of Directors of the [[Kestner Evaporating Co.]] and on the Board of Trustees of the [[Cummington School]] in [[Massachusetts]].<ref name="philadelphia"/>

===Personal life===
He died on January 1st, 1940.<ref name="philadelphia"/><ref name="pacific"/>

